ce:section.ce:para:
According to reported literatures, many analytical methods have been established for determination of 2,4-dinitroaniline. For example, Wang’s group proposed a new monolith-based adsorbent (MBA) as extraction phases of home-made multichannel in-tip microextraction apparatus combining with HPLC for determination of 2,4-dinitroaniline. The method exhibited good sensitivity with LOD of 0.014 μg L−1. Wu et al developed electro-enhanced solid phase microextraction (EE-SPME) based on porous monolith doped with carboxylic carbon nanotubes (M@CCNs) for the analysis of 2,4-dinitroaniline, which resulted in excellent sensitivity with LOD of 0.012 μg L−1 
                        [34,35]. These methods possessed good sensitivity due to highly efficient sample pretreatment technologies in combination with highly sensitive instruments. Meanwhile but they often consumed more time and manpower. Relatively speaking, fluorescent sensor is a simple and rapid way for measuring pollutants. The fluorescent sensor prepared in this work was proved to be reliable for quantitative analysis of 2,4-dinitroaniline. Compared with other reported fluorescent sensors for the detection of 2,4-dinitroaniline, the proposed sensor exhibited better detection performance than some reported methods and required lesser synthesis time although its sensitivity was a little higher than one of the established methods [36–38]. Moreover, the interaction of CDs and 2,4-dinitroaniline was quite rapid and the measurement could be conducted just in one minute, which also saved a lot of time for analysis of target analytes (Table 2
                        ).
